image.altText: A close-up photo of a woman.

props.synopsis: After 36 years working as a house cleaner, Judy Harman needs a knee replacement, but there are hundreds of people in front of her on the wait list for orthopaedic surgery in Canberra.

title.children: Judy is crippled with pain as she waits for surgery in Canberra

image.altText: Drone Main

props.synopsis: Police allege the the man was trying to deliver drugs, nicotine patches, USB sticks and a smart watch to prisoners inside a Canberra jail.

title.children: Young father caught allegedly flying drone into Canberra prison to drop drugs

image.altText: Alexander Maconochie Centre is Canberra's only prison.

props.synopsis: The ACT government will expand the use of electronic body scanners to the courts after their use in Canberra's only prison saw a dramatic drop in the need to strip search prisoners.

title.children: Body scanner use in Canberra significantly reduces prison strip searches

image.altText: Mal holds up the gun in the air, wearing a red jacket.

props.synopsis: It was 25 years ago when Cathy Freeman crossed the line into history, winning gold in the 400m at the 2000 Olympics, a moment that's vivid in the memory of gun starter Mal Davies.

title.children: As Cathy Freeman eyed a gold medal, this man pulled the starting trigger

image.altText: Scene of light rail death Canberra

props.synopsis: A 49-year-old Canberra man died after being struck by a light rail vehicle on Saturday evening.

title.children: Man dies after being hit by light rail vehicle in Canberra

image.altText: An artist's render of a modern theatre building at sunset, with a few hundred people standing out the front.

props.synopsis: Detailed designs show plans for the new 2,000-seat lyric theatre, inspired by Canberra's natural landmarks, which will host major musicals, ballets and operas.

title.children: 'Scale and sophistication': New Canberra lyric theatre designs revealed

image.altText: Del sticks her tongue out, pretending to be a cat and wearing her costume and sitting near the stage.

props.synopsis: By day, Canberra public servant Del Goncalves works in a typical office and wears typical office clothes, but come nightfall, she dons a bunny costume and trades her office for a wrestling ring.

title.children: Canberra car dealers and public servants by day, pro wrestlers by night

image.altText: A painting of Costa Georgiadis surrounded by trees, insects and animals.

props.synopsis: The National Portrait Gallery invited the public to identify a person who was missing from its collection — the winner, chosen from a shortlist of 25 remarkable Australians, was Gardening Australia host Costa Georgiadis.

title.children: Painting of Costa Georgiadis unveiled at National Portrait Gallery

image.altText: Nick Kyrgios stands in front of a microphone, flanked by two ACT politicians.

props.synopsis: Construction on a new $9.9 million tennis facility in the Gungahlin has begun five years after the ACT government pledged funding for it ahead of the 2020 territory election.

title.children: Nick Kyrgios spruiks construction of $9.9m tennis facility in Canberra's north

image.altText: A close-up of Anthony Albanese.

props.synopsis: This year's Boyer Lectures will consider whether our democratic system will hold in the face of global headwinds.

title.children: Will Australia's democracy survive global collapse?

image.altText: A close up of a middle aged woman with a worried expression, looking up and to her left.

props.synopsis: With Hamas yet to provide its response to Donald Trump's peace plan, affected civilians on both sides of the war share their concerns and hopes for the future.

title.children: Israeli hostage families and Palestinians in nervous wait over Gaza peace plan

image.altText: Three photos of Sergeant Morey with his hands around Sean Beasley's neck.

props.synopsis: A man who alleges he was choked by an off-duty police officer in front of his daughter says he has lost trust in the police force, after they found "insufficient evidence" to lay charges over the road incident.

title.children: Perth dad reveals details of alleged choking by off-duty police officer

image.altText: A surfer balancing on a board on a wave.

props.synopsis: The disastrous algal bloom that has been, for at least six months, lapping at South Australia's shores has turned a coastline into a frontline. It's left many swimmers, surfers and seaside business operators wondering what the upcoming summer will look like.

title.children: The sea is sick and has entered uncharted waters

image.altText: Minister Anika Wells wearing a grey jacket and white blouse speaking at a media conference.

props.synopsis: Touted in some insider circles as future Labor leadership material, self-identified millennial Anika Wells finds herself in a storm over the nation's emergency triple-0 system.

title.children: Optus crisis opens a political vulnerability for Coalition to seize upon

image.altText: The headshots of two men in suits are side-by-side in the same image.

props.synopsis: Australia and Türkiye are at loggerheads over who will host the massive international event, with insiders suggesting the countries could share the hosting rights.

title.children: Australia and Türkiye hit impasse over global climate summit

image.altText: Pete Hegseth

props.synopsis: Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth summoned hundreds of US military officials to an in-person meeting to declare an end to "woke" culture in the military.

title.children: Hegseth slams 'fat generals' and diversity initiatives in US military

image.altText: The terrain near Yunta.

props.synopsis: The search for a four-year-old boy who remains missing in South Australia's north days after he disappeared is shifting towards a "recovery" phase despite the discovery of a footprint, police have said.

title.children: Footprint found but search for missing boy moving to 'recovery' phase

image.altText: A human egg before fertilisation.

props.synopsis: Scientists have used human skin cells to produce functional eggs using a new scientific technique they say could one day help infertile people have their own biological children.

title.children: Human embryo made with skin may one day produce two-dad babies

image.altText: A wide shot of iron ore being loaded onto a ship in Port Hedland.

props.synopsis: Anthony Albanese says any restriction on iron ore markets is disappointing, as BHP remains tight-lipped. Follow the day's events and insights from our business reporters on the ABC News live markets blog.

title.children: BHP shares slide as miner tight-lipped on ban reports

liveBlogKeyEvents.title: BHP iron ore supply 'irreplaceable' for China

image.altText: Keith Urban and Nicole Kidman on the red carpet prior to the Oscars ceremony.

props.synopsis: The Oscar-winning actor files for divorce in a Nashville court a day after reports emerged of the couple's separation, with a source saying the decision to leave was Keith Urban's.

title.children: Kidman and Urban divorce a month in the making, court documents show

image.altText: an illustration showing a young person sitting against a wall on a skateboard, with court symbols

props.synopsis: The ABC spent a week inside the court that presides over youth crime and witnessed fearful victims, young people living with trauma and magistrates facing the difficult to decision to bail or remand.

title.children: 'I'm at my wit's end': A week inside a children's court

image.altText: Jeff Schoep sitting in Chesterfield chair.

props.synopsis: Former US Neo-Nazi leader Jeff Schoep urges the Australian media not to publicise the actions of Neo-Nazis, after attending protests to gain insights into extremism in Victoria.

title.children: American ex-Neo-Nazi takes 'peace building' mission to Victoria

image.altText: Afghan girls attend a religious studies class dressed in traditional black robes.

props.synopsis: Internet and mobile services have been cut across the country, a move human rights groups say will severely impact women and girls in particular.

title.children: Women and girls severely impacted by telecom blackout in Afghanistan

image.altText: Men holding "SCRAP THE PLAN" signs.

props.synopsis: The controversial housing plan that would see 31,000 apartments built in the inner west was passed by one vote on Tuesday night.

title.children: Councillors booed, cheered after plan for 31,000 new Sydney homes passes

image.altText: Napheesa Collier and Caitlin Clark sit and smile at NBA All Star weekend.

props.synopsis: WNBA superstar Napheesa Collier goes scorched earth on the league's leadership, criticising a lack of accountability and revealing some alarming comments by commissioner Cathy Engelbert.

title.children: WNBA boss allegedly says Caitlin Clark should be 'grateful' despite $78k salary

image.altText: Roslyn Grima sits in the sun outside her home. A dachshund lays at her feet.

props.synopsis: A court has granted Roslyn Grima the right to list her caravan park home on the market, but whether she can legally make a sale remains in dispute.

title.children: Caravan park resident with months to live can list her home for sale, court rules

image.altText: An oil painting showing fields and a reaper

props.synopsis: A "rarely seen" collection of works from renowned artists Vincent van Gogh, Claude Monet and Henri Matisse will be on display in Adelaide next year, as part of 57 works on loan from the Toledo Museum of Art in the US.

title.children: Van Gogh painting to be displayed in Adelaide for first time

image.altText: A person works on his computer at a workstation.

props.synopsis: The economic contribution of start-ups has been overlooked, as a new study suggests age and performance should be taken into consideration when it comes to incentive policy.

title.children: When it comes to business, size does matter — and smaller isn't necessarily better

image.altText: A man wearing glasses and a brown shirt.

props.synopsis: The Riyadh Comedy Festival stars A-list comedians like Peter Davidson, but despite its blockbuster acts, it has copped backlash for what one human rights organisation says is a "whitewashing" of a "brutal repression of free speech".

title.children: Why stars are 'disgusted' at those performing at a Saudi comedy festival

image.altText: Fresh vegetables in a commercial fridge.

props.synopsis: A community group in an outback town is fighting high prices to offer more affordable food, clothing, and other essentials that were previously only available hundreds of kilometres away.

title.children: Outback community turns vision for cheaper essentials into reality

image.altText: Katrina Munting wears a bright patterned shirt and stands near trees on an overcast day.

props.synopsis: Victim-survivor Katrina Munting says she remains hopeful, but she is concerned the government isn't implementing the commission of inquiry's recommendations quickly enough.

title.children: 'Was it worth it?' Two years on from Tasmania's child sexual abuse report

image.altText: Red rock with various animals etched in including camels and goats, highlighted with blue tracing.

props.synopsis: Three newly discovered sites filled with art and stone tools have pushed back the date on when humans returned to Arabia after the last ice age.

title.children: Mystery artists carved life-sized camels into rocks 12,000 years ago

image.altText: A woman looks at the myTax website on a computer screen, resting her head on her hand.

props.synopsis: The 2024/25 tax deadline is fast approaching, and missing the cut-off date could end up costing you. Here's what you need to know.

title.children: Haven't done your tax return yet? You have one month left

image.altText: Man with white hair, in blue suit, waving hat

props.synopsis: Disgraced former MP Gareth Ward was paid a weekly salary of more than $3,000 while waiting to be sentenced for sexual offences. An Illawarra resident wants to ensure that never happens again.

title.children: Voter launches petition to stop convicted MPs being paid in jail

image.altText: Water with black swirls and clouds floating between two poles.

props.synopsis: Building company Boral works to clean up thousands of litres of kerosene and bitumen from one of its plants that have spilled into a creek in Cairns, connecting to an inlet that leads to the Great Barrier Reef.

title.children: Clean-up underway after 'devastating' industrial spill in Far North Queensland
